        <div class="bento-cta">See full review <span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">How we picked these tools</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">We tested <span class="accent">dozens of social media tools</span> across 70+ local business industries.</h2>
      <p>We publish social media content for local businesses across 70+ industries and have tested every major social media tool on the market. This list covers only tools with permanent free plans — not trials, not freemium tiers that expire, not "free with credit card." Real free plans that handle real tasks local businesses need.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col before">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Our inclusion criteria</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">3 rules for this list. No exceptions.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">If a tool didn't meet all three, it didn't make the cut.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Permanent free plan — not a trial</h4>
              <p>No 7-day free trials. No free plans that require a credit card. Every tool on this list offers features that remain free indefinitely.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Genuinely useful for local businesses specifically</h4>
              <p>Not just general-purpose tools. Each tool must solve a real problem local businesses face — scheduling, design, local presence, analytics, or content creation.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Free plan works without the paid upgrade for core use</h4>
              <p>The free tier must handle the core task. If the free plan is so limited it forces an upgrade to do anything useful, it's a marketing tool — not a free product.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ba-col after">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">The honest truth about free tools</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Free tools save money but not time. Here's the real math.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Know the trade-off before you commit to a free-only stack.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>1–2 posts per day costs 5–10 hours per month in owner time</h4>
              <p>At $50–$100/hour in owner time, "free" social media tools cost $250–$1,000 per month in labor. That's the real price of the free stack.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Google Business Profile is the most important social channel — and it's free</h4>
              <p>GBP posts directly influence local search rankings. The free tier of your GBP profile is more valuable than any paid social media tool if you're trying to rank locally.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>The free stack works — until consistency fails</h4>
              <p>Most local businesses start with free tools and post consistently for 4–8 weeks. Then life intervenes. Posting drops. Engagement falls. The free stack only works if you actually use it consistently.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>$49/month eliminates the consistency problem entirely</h4>
              <p>theStacc's Social Media module publishes 30 posts per month automatically. No time investment. No consistency risk. The break-even vs. manual posting time is less than 1 hour of owner time per month.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Build a free stack first — upgrade when it works</h4>
              <p>Use the free tools to validate your social media strategy. Once you know which channels drive customers, automate those channels with a paid tool. Don't automate before you've tested.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STATS ROW -->
  <section>
